 {
"Topic": "Administration of lithium prophylaxis",
"Content": "Lithium is a commonly used drug for the prophylaxis, or prevention, of bipolar disorder. It works by stabilizing the mood of the patient. The usual dosage for lithium maintenance therapy ranges from 0.6 to 1.2 millimoles per liter (mmol/L) in the blood. The therapeutic effect is typically achieved after several weeks of treatment. Lithium can cause side effects such as thirst, frequent urination, tremors, and gastrointestinal symptoms. Long-term use of lithium can lead to nephrogenic diabetes insipidus, a condition characterized by excessive urination and dehydration. Other drugs that may be used in combination with lithium include valproic acid and olanzapine. Valproic acid helps to reduce the risk of mood swings and may also help to prevent seizures. Olanzapine is an atypical antipsychotic that can help to alleviate symptoms of mania and depression. Close monitoring of lithium levels in the blood is essential to ensure effective treatment and to minimize side effects."
}

"Cited drugs": ["lithium", "valproic acid", "olanzapine"]

