Summary:
This text discusses the interactions between cobalt and iron in the context of their absorption and retention in the human body. The text explains that both cobalt and iron are essential minerals, but their absorption can be influenced by each other. Iron is more readily absorbed when the dietary intake of cobalt is low, while high cobalt intake can inhibit iron absorption. This inhibitory effect is thought to be due to the competitive binding of these minerals to transport proteins in the gastrointestinal tract. The text also mentions that cobalt can be retained in the body more effectively when iron levels are low.

