 Title: Intestinal Absorption of Arsenate in the Chick

Summary:
This study investigates the intestinal absorption of arsenate in chickens. The researchers used radiolabeled arsenate ([32P]AsO43-) to trace the absorption and distribution of arsenate in the chick intestine. They found that arsenate absorption occurred primarily in the proximal small intestine, with the highest absorption rate observed in the duodenum. The absorption rate decreased as the intestinal length increased. The study also revealed that arsenate absorption was influenced by the presence of other ions, such as phosphate and calcium.

Key Findings:
- Arsenate absorption occurred primarily in the proximal small intestine of chickens.
- The highest absorption rate was observed in the duodenum.
- Arsenate absorption was influenced by the presence of other ions, such as phosphate and calcium.

Cited Drugs:
None mentioned in the text.

