 Title: Acute Effect of Different Antidepressants on Glycemia in Diabetic and Non-Diabetic Rats

Summary:
This study investigates the acute impact of various antidepressants on glycemia in diabetic and non-diabetic rats. The antidepressants used in this experiment were Fluoxetine, Paroxetine, Sertraline, and Imipramine.

Experimental Design:
The study was conducted in two groups: diabetic and non-diabetic rats. Each group was further divided into four subgroups, with each subgroup receiving a different antidepressant treatment: Fluoxetine, Paroxetine, Sertraline, or Imipramine. The rats were given a single oral dose of the respective antidepressant, and their blood glucose levels were measured at regular intervals for 2 hours.

Results:
The findings revealed that all antidepressants caused a significant increase in glycemia in both diabetic and non-diabetic rats. However, the extent of the increase varied between the antidepressants and the rat groups.

